SequenceEvent: Driver states to BC that PH had HazMat staged on the floor and he moved to a shelf. He believes he hit a bump and it caused the package to burst on the shelf and leak in the van onto other packages. DescribePack: 1.5 gallons of Zep cleaner leaked from bottom of the Gallon bottles in fiberboard box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Driver was instructed to pull over and open the doors of the vehicle. He called the Emergency Response number on the HazMat paperwork but was not assisted. BC met driver and they were able to transfer damaged packages in the back of a straight truck. All cleanup materials were put in a bag and given to PDM upon return. After cleanup, driver did not feel at risk and continued on with his day. Upon return to the station, PDM - Kayla Hoback - equipped PPE (mask, gloves, apron, etc.) and put all damaged packages onto a damage pallet to thoroughly inspect each one. Only 4 packages truly damaged and the remaining were repacked and sent out to customers.

At 1042 ET, Schneider Bulk contacted ERTS to report a hazardous cargo release. It was reported 50-100 gallons of UN 1814 "Conquest" released due to tank overflow while the driver was performing a delivery at Zentis Food 2050 North Oak Dr, Plymouth, IN. It was reported no drains, soil or waterways were impacted.  RMS arrived on site and advised 100ft by 30ft area on concrete inside the facility was impacted and migrated outside the building onto a 15ft by 20ft area of concrete. No drains or waterways were impacted. RMS utilized a pump to collect as much free standing liquid as possible, then utilize a neutralizing absorbent to clean the remaining areas. At 1505 ET, RMS advised they utilizied Chemsorb CA to clean and neutralize the impacted areas. ERTS reached out to RMS for an update. The contractor advised they have begun applying a 30% white vinegar solution to the impacted areas of the spill as the Chemsorb was not proving effective. The vinegar solution has been getting much better results and they have noted no hazardous reactions. The team sprayed the solution and then used spill pads to remove the liquid/residue. All waste was staged on site at the facility until profiled and properly disposed.

SequenceEvent: Package was picked up from a driver on the day of 12/14/23 and brought back to the station. Upon arrival of QA Calvin Pudela (12/15/23 @ 12:00PM), a noticeable odor of alcohol was coming from the pail. Once I flipped the pail over, I noticed that there was a slight amount of liquid coming out. Then I started my processing of HAZMAT package. DescribePack: There is a cap built into the top cap for the pail of denatured alcohol. The cap appears to have been opened and no longer seems to close/seal. DurationRel: 6 and MitigateEffect: I taped the cap of the pail opening to avoid anymore of the smell escaping.

column169: Driver reached out due to having issues when trying to offload.  Safety determined there was a leak on top of the trailer, and it wouldn’t build pressure.  Safety told the driver to stop what she was doing and reached out to another driver close by to see if he could assist, then called the AMLO terminal.  They found there was a check valve failure, and it wouldn’t close.  They also found the trailer didn’t have some of the fittings needed and the other driver supplied them.  Bleeder fitting was on the other end at customers connection instead of truck side. Driver couldn’t connect it to truck side due to not having the correct fittings so she connected to customers end connection before it goes into the building.   When Driver went to open an ear on the fitting, it sprayed out, and they didn’t realize pressure was on the hose.   Customer mentioned it was water soluble and sprayed down concrete with water and the drivers’ chemical suits.  Driver mentions that after talking with the customer, their valve was open on the inside of the building and their system had pressure on it causing to backflow into the truck hose.  Customer closed valve inside building and both drivers drain what they could in the hoses and cap hoses.  After the repair was completed on the vacuum breaker she went back to unload at customer.
column170: Driver was re-coached on what should have been done first before touching the equipment.  All unloading procedures for this location was retrained.

column169: On December 13, 2023, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN1760 was crushed in transit and released approximately fifteen (15) gallons of product to the trailer interior and dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel successfully transferred the contents from the damaged 330-gallon tote to a new 330-gallon tote for further shipment and processing. Crews utilized hand tools to cut up the damaged tote for waste, and they utilized a neutralizing solution and absorbent pads to remediate the impacted dock floor. Four (4) 55-gallon drums containing the cut-up tote, spent absorbent pads, damaged metal fittings, and impacted cardboard were generated as waste and staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal LLA experienced a UN1866 ELAN-Cast P 300 S RTC Low Odor release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons of material released to the entire trailer floor as well as a 30’ x 20’ area of the concrete lot below due to the trailer wall puncturing the tote. The puncture was patched with wood to stop the release and the material was transferred into a new tote for shipment on. The free-standing liquid material was collected with a drum vac into (2) 55-gallon metal drums. Floor dry was then deployed and worked into the impacted areas and then collected into a third 55-gallon metal drum. The punctured tote was patched with absorbent pads & chemical tape. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On 12/15/2023 at approximately 1345  , Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 68727 at the station location in Groveland, reporting a herbicide spill.  The shipment consisted of one plastic container that shipped inside of a fiberboard box. The shipment was discovered leaking, initially the cause was unknown.  The shipment was discovered leaking during delivery and was returned to the station,  Further investigation revealed that the top was not secure on the bottle, causing the spillage. An online safety data sheet was located by Dangerous Goods Administration and it revealed that the commodity was  classified as a regulated corrosive shipment, though not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations.  The shipment is being held pending an FAA investigation.

While in transit, (1) box containing (2) 1-gallon bottles of Blue Whale Muriatic Acid (UN1789) became crushed as a result of inadequate preparation for transportation. During the off-loading process, the damaged, crushed product began leaking onto the concrete dock floor; a total amount of 1-gallon. A Contractor neutralized the release using Kolorsafe Liquid Acid Neutralizer before absorbing the liquid and containerizing the spill debris into the proper UN-rated shipping container (a vented 55-gallon fiber drum). Additionally, the pallet in which the load was shipped on was also cut-up and containerized for waste disposal. Lastly, the impacted box that the leaking bottles shipped in was neutralized and containerized for waste disposal. No storm drains, waterways, or soil were impacting by the release.

The trailer was fine until it arrived to offload.  Once they started offloading the trailer began dripping 2 drips every 5 seconds.  They were able to contain the leak to a bucket and finished the offload so it could be sent for repairs.  We're a bit surprised it started leaking at the time it did.  Usually when doing a pump offload it creates a 'vacuum' away from the source of the leak and slows it down.  In this case this is when it started leaking.  I likely has to do with when the internal valve was opened though that allowed it to get to the sump gasket.  That is what actually leaked.
column170: Its hard to say if the gasket was bad due to age / deterioration or if the valve bolts werent torqued enough anymore.  The trailer is coming due for its annual inspection.  This is not something we are seeing repeat incidents of and feel this is an isolated incident and do not see the need for any operational changes at this time.

SequenceEvent: The driver that had this package on his truck was out delivering when he discovered the leaking hazmat. He put the package in plastic bags to try to contain the spill. He set the package on the passenger side steps while QA investigated. One QA person called the emergency number who stated they could someone out to clean up or we could clean up if we felt we could handle it. QA placed the package in a red hazmat tote. QA sprinkled the area with neutralizing powder as a safety measure. The spill was soaked up and the clean up materials placed in the salvage drum. DescribePack: The top of the cap on the bottle has broken off. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed in a lined red hazmat tote and put into a well ventilated area. column169: On December 8, 2023, one (1) 2.5 gallon jug of ZeroTol 2.0 was crushed in transit and released approximately less than one (<1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Ten West Environmental (TWE) to remediate the impacted site. TWE personnel utilized hand tools, absorbents, and soda ash to remediate the ZeroTol-impacted impacted trailer. The crew de palletized, re palletized, and shrink wrapped the freight for the customer. TWE personnel solidified and neutralized the damaged jug of product. The damaged jug and all impacted debris were collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon poly vented drums and stored on site for transport and disposal.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GMES) to remediate the impacted site.  GMES personnel removed all contaminated poly wrap to inspect the drum. Crews utilized rags and a neutralizing solution to collect the released product from the top and sides of the drum. GMES personnel utilized an 85-gallon open top drum to overpack and contain the damaged 55-gallon drum. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 30-gallon drum. All containers were staged onsite for future disposal.

ERTS dispatched E3 to the site to perform the clean up and tank transfer.  E3 arrived on site and with proper hazmat attire advised an estimated 30 gallons were released to a 8ft by 8ft area of asphalt. E3 contained the spill then conducted the tank transfer, once completed the team will work on the asphalt area.  The relief tank and damaged tanker were removed from the site with approval from MS DEQ.  The impacted area was scraped with shovels, soda ash was applied to the area and then collected it. There was a second asphalt area impacted that was 3ft x 3ft where the driver entered the property this area was cleaned up. three poly drums of impacted solids were generated and will be staged at 3421 Industrial Rd Pascagoula MS until profiled and properly disposed of.

column169: On December 5, 2023 at 1200 hrs., FRA Hazmat Inspector discovered what appeared to be product running down the sides of PNWX 703091 (Load / UN 3082 / Class 9 / PG III) at CN Geismar Yard.  The liquid on the exterior of the railcar was observed coming from the manway.  The inspector climbed the railcar and attempted to turn the manway cover bolts by hand but was unsuccessful.  The FRA Inspector notified the Dangerous Goods Officer.  The Dangerous Goods Officer made all notifications. CN Response Contractor responded and upon approaching the railcar observed moisture on the exterior of the railcar coming from the manway area.  Upon further investigation, the manway gasket was found to be pinched which did not provide proper securement of the manway closure.  The manway gasket was properly installed, and manway was secured.  The exterior of the railcar was decontaminated and returned to Transportation.
THE RESPONDER WAS MADE AWARE OF A DAMP HAZMAT PACKAGE. THE RESPONDER DONNED FULL PPE AND COLLECTED THE PACKAGE FOR PROCESSING.

column169: On December 21, 2023, at 1945 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Laredo, Texas regarding the release of a total of (2) quarts of SHIELD-BRITE ® VACATE (UN1719 Caustic Alkali Liquids, n.o.s. (Sodium Hydroxide, Potassium Hydroxide) 8, II) from (6) 5-gallon plastic pails. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release was caused by defective seals in the caps on top of the pails and contained to a 5’ x 6’ area on the trailer floor. Contractors were able to neutralize the release and clean it with absorbents and the proper PPE. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (1) 55-gallon DF, and recovered product was placed in (2) 55-gallon DF's and then taken offsite by contractors.

column169: On December 19, 2023, at 0711 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by A Duie Pile personnel in Newburgh, NY regarding the release of an unknown amount of various products due to a multiple vehicle accident (The speed of the vehicle is unknown). Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of multiple materials which included KEM AQUA® 400 Waterborne Enamel (UN1263, 3, III), Polane Plus Enamel (Part A) (UN1263, 3, III), and a Flammable Liquid, Corrosive, n.o.s. (UN1263, 3, II). Contractors were unable to assess approximately how much of each were released due to the materials mixing with each other. Contractors were able to clean the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. All waste generated was containerized in (7) 55-gallon poly drum, and (7) 55-gallon metal drum which was then taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

On December 16, 2023, at approximately 14:24 hours, personnel at the CSX Parkersburg, WV yard reported an odor of gas coming from the area of tank TILX 305535, residue: last contained Isoprene, stabilized. SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, responded and found TILX 305535 leaking from the top of the tank car.  The tank car was isolated and the Shipper, Kraton Corp, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2023-1216-00057).  SPSI inspected the railcar and found the sample line valve not fully closed and the secondary closure plug less than tool tight.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Kel Fann (904-239-2238, Michael.Fann@kraton.com). Contractor personnel closed the sample line valve and secured the secondary closure plug.  The car was released for transportation.

column169: Veolia employees were at Veolia's 10-day intransit facility in Gurabo, PR when they detected a strong odor coming from one of the trailers. Further investigation revealed that a 55 gallon drum had over pressurized and spilled chemicals. The spill was contained within the trailer and did not exit out or under the trailer. The Veolia employees cleaned up the spill caused by the overpressure of the drum and put the drum inside a 851H2 overpack, the residues of material collected from the spill were also put inside the same overpack.
column170: Veolia has been picking up from this customer for about 5 years on a frequency of once every 1-2 weeks from the customer's waste storage area and has never had this issue before. The customer would put an inhibitor into the containers when they were placed in the storage area and they would sit in storage for at least a week until Veolia picked them up. The customer recently demolished their on-site storage area for building additions and requested Veolia to come weekly for service pick ups. Historically, the customer would apply hydroquinone as an inhibitor to the waste at least 48 hours prior to Veolia's pick up service to ensure neutralization and any reaction is completed prior to offering the drums for transportation. Following the incident, discussion with the customer revealed that the hydroquinone was added to the waste drum on the same day Veolia picked up the waste container. The hydroquinone inhibitor should be applied at least 48 hours prior to our pick up service to ensure the neutralization reaction is completed. The practice of the 48 hour waiting period was done in all previous service pick ups with no incidents. The customer has agreed to apply the hydroquinone inhibitor on Fridays to ensure the neutralization reaction is completed prior to Veolia picking up the waste on Mondays. The Veolia employees will monitor this procedure very closely and validate in advance the date and time of inhibitor application prior to pick up the drums.

On 12-23-2023 a CN transportation employee observed liquid dripping from the bottom outlet valve cap during routing work operations at the CN Waterloo Yard in Waterloo, IA.  The employee notified the Yard Supervisor who then initiated an emergency response from the CN Dangerous Goods Team. The responding DG Officer observed liquid dripping from the BOV cap which was found to be tool tight (could not turn by hand). The shipper's security seal was not found. BOV handle was in the fully closed position. It was determined that there was a failure in the sealing surface of the valve seat to include a defective or missing BOV gasket. The BOV handle was cycled several times from the closed to open position to ensure there was no foreign material trapped in the valve seat that would prevent a proper seal. The cap was then removed, and the valve was monitored for 10 minutes for any continued leakage. There was no longer any leakage from the valve at this point. An inspection of the BOV cap gasket was performed and revealed it to be very stiff allowing the product to leak past the gasket. The BOV gasket was replaced, and the cap re-installed utilizing a 24" pipe wrench.

On 12/19/23, the CPDX 109139 was found with frosting on the protective housing on top of the car.  El Segundo Fire and Chevron Fire responded to conduct air monitoring around the site and inspect the car.  Upon inspection, liquid LPG was found coming from the liquid valve.  The valve was partially open.  Responders closed the valve which had stopped the leak.  BNSF responders inspected the car and also determined that the liquid valve plug was less than tool tight.  Air monitoring was conducted to verify integrity of repairs with pressure on the valve and plug.

Hepaco  was  dispatched  to  the  site.  Upon  the contractor’s  arrival,  personnel  observed  that  the  released  material  impacted  a  4ft-by-4ft  area  of  the concrete terminal floor and estimated that two (2) gallons of material was released due to a puncture during improper unloading  to one (1) 330-gallon metal tote. Hepaco personnel applied a patch kit to the damaged weld seam on the metal tote and containerized the impacted carboard that was used by terminal personnel as absorbents into one 55-gallon metal drum along with absorbent pads and PPE used  by  Hepaco  personnel.  The  generated  waste  was  staged  onsite  at  the  terminal  prior  to  the contractor  demobilization  and  will  remain  onsite  for  Dayton  Freight’s  contracted  hazardous  waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

column43: AMMONIUM NITRATE EMULSION OR AMMONIUM NITRATE SUSPENSION OR AMMONIUM NITRATE GEL, INTERMEDIATE FOR BLASTING EXPLOSIVES
column169: On 11/30/2023, 45,660 pounds of Ammonium Nitrate Emulsion (ANE) was loaded into trailer 974 through the rearmost hatch. After loading was completed, the rear hatch was not closed and latched by the loader.  On 12/1/2023, the driver coupled to the trailer and departed Barry, IL and drove to Buckley Powder Company in Hermann, MO.  The driver arrived, unloaded into the product tower, and traveled back in reverse order on the same route.  The trailer was uncoupled Barry, IL. Employees at site observed ANE residue on the side of the trailer.  Buckley Powder Company found spots of ANE residue on their private gravel road totaling less than ten (10) pounds, which they cleaned up and disposed of properly.  It is estimated 5,247 pounds of ANE was lost in transit between Barry, IL and Hermann, MO.   It was raining on 12/1/2023. Dyno Nobel employees inspected the roadways of IL 106 and US 54 and there was not any evidence of residue on the roadway. The Buckley Powder manager inspected Loutre Bend Rd and did not observe residue on the road.
column170: The company will conduct refresher training on pre/post-trip inspections, and the site supervisor will review the company employee accountability program with the drivers.  The company will continue with the HazMat spot checks to ensure compliance with the hazardous materials regulations.

All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum to be staged onsite for future disposal. LSH personnel transferred the product from the damaged 330-gallon tote to one (1) new 330-gallon tote for further shipment.

On December 26, 2023, six (6) one-gallon pails of UN1789 released approximately two (2) gallons of product due to loose lids. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Ancon Services (AS) to remediate the impacted site. AS personnel utilized absorbent pads and a neutralizing solution to wipe down the impacted freight and dock floor.  One (1) vented 30-gallon drum of the six (6) damaged 1-gallon plastic jugs and two (2) 55-gallon drums of impacted pads, the cut-up pallet, and any cleanup debris were generated as waste and staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

Hepaco  was  dispatched  to  the  site.  Upon  the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 70ft-by-20ft area of the concrete terminal floor and estimated that seventy (70) gallons of material was released due to forklift damaging one (1) 275-gallon poly tote. Hepaco personnel deployed a neutralizer to the impacted area while on SCBA and later respirators and later once the neutralizing had been completed an absorbent was  used  to  gather  the  spent  material.  Hepaco  personnel  recovered  the  spent  material  and containerized it into eight  (8) 55-gallon poly drums. The  remaining product in the damaged tote was transferred to a new tote and the damaged 275-gallon poly tote was cut up and placed into one (1) 55- gallon poly drum. The generated waste was staged onsite in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization.  The  generated  waste  will  remain  onsite  for  the  ESTES  DGRM  team  to  coordinate disposal.

column169: Car found to be leaking from the bottom outlet cap at a rate of 2-3 gallons per minute.  Upon arrival of the contractor, Code 3, the valve handle was in the closed, pinned, and sealed position and the bottom outlet cap was less than tool tight.  Code 3 tightened the cap, stopping the release.  After the car was set out, the contractor was able to climb under the car and determined that the valve was in the open position even with the handle closed.  The handle was dropped to the open position, engaged, and the valve closed.  The BOV plug was removed and verified the valve was closed with no release.  The shipper was contacted and an OTMA was requested before the car would be released into transportation.

While unloading a pallet of waste from a trailer at Veolia's ten day intransit facility, a Veolia employee heard a pop and realized the forks on the forklift were protruding out of the back of the pallet and punctured a 15 gallon 1H1 drum of flammable liquid located on the pallet behind the one he was moving. Approximately 100 ml of the material leaked out before the hole closed on itself. The employee moved the forklift away from the area and shut it off, then proceeded to contain the spill with absorbent. The employee and the Veolia site manager then donned correct PPE and promptly overpacked the container and cleaned up the spill area.
column170: The Veolia employee needs to be aware of the length of their forks on the forklift in reference to the material they are handling and ensure that their forks do not protrude out the back of the pallet they are working on. Also whenever possible use a spotter to ensure safe loading practices.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal LSL experienced a UN1993 WCW6400 Combination Product release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to complete cleanup and a liquid tote transfer. Contractors arrived onsite and liaised with onsite LSP contact, Jay Hardy. Crew confirmed approximately 1.5-ounces of product released to the tote lid only which was padded up with an absorbent pad. The release was caused by a crack to the top corner of the tote as a result of improper loading. The product was then transferred via pump, at the requested of the LSP, into a new tote for shipment on. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbent pads and PPE into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: Passenger Drake Cox informed us of his laptop overheating inside of his backpack. When we got out the fire containment bag, he decided to bring the whole backpack to us. We put on the heat resistant gloves and a second Flight Attendant helped me with pouring a Iiter of water on the inside of the fire containment bag. I removed the laptop from the backpack and placed it in the fire containment bag with the battery facing down. The second Flight Attendant cleared out a galley cart and we placed the fire containment bag in the furthest aircraft right galley cart in the AFT of the aircraft. We continued to monitor the laptop throughout the rest of the flight, but no further action was needed. Once we arrived and all the passengers deplaned, the entire cart was brought to the forward galley as per the Supervisofs request and that's when the Supervisor told us Flight Attendants we were ok to leave and the rest would be taken care of. The laptop was an Apple MacBook Pro.

The box with leaking liquid and was placed in a hazmat cart wrapped in hazmat bag and processed into a hazmat drum to be held for disposition. DescribePack: The entire box was wet from chemicals that spilled in box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The box with leaking liquid was placed in a hazmat cart wrapped in hazmat bag and processed into a hazmat drum to be held for disposition.
